Title: Women Against Violence Against Women (WAVAW) Collection
Description.abstract: The Women Against Violence Against Women(WAVAW) Collection is a mixture of papers and organizational records, publications, ephemera and audio-visual materials collected by organization member Dani Adams (national office in Los Angeles). Of particular interest are the internal memos and complete run of national newsletters produced by the Los Angeles Chapter for national chapter distribution and slides and scripts from the WAVAW slide show, the presentation that chapter members showed to audiences nationwide. There is also extensive coverage of WAVAW's actions against the film "Snuff" and the Rolling Stones' "Black and Blue" advertising campaign and national boycott of Warner Communications, Inc. (WCI).

Description.note: Women Against Violence Against Women Collection: Box 3, 6 Folders.|~|Articles of Incorporation of Pacific Coast Media Center (WAVAW's corporate parent) and Articles of Incorporation of Women Against Violence Against Women (WAVAW); copy of the letter whereby Pacific Coast Media Center (PCMC) established WAVAW as a PCMC project, copy of the letter from the IRS establishing PCMC as a nonprofit educational organization and correspondence authorizing various WAVAW chapters to establish WAVAW offices. Founding document re first action that gets Women Against Violence Against Women (WAVAW) organized. Finances/affiliation with other groups, individuals working with women Against Violence Against Women (WAVAW). City of Los Angeles Resolution. What is WAVAW? Fact Sheet.

Name.correspondent: Los Angeles Feminist Women’s Health Center|~|Snyder, Arthur K.
Title: Letter protesting the release of "Snuff" in Los Angeles
Description.note: Document is signed by:Los Angeles Feminist Women's Health Center, Orange County Feminist Women's Health Center, Lesbian Tide, Olivia records, California Now Inc., Feminist Lawyers, Califia Community Collective, Hollywood-Silverlake Consciousness Raising Group, Guild of Feminist Authors, Radical Feminist Therapy Collective, Sisterhood Bookstore|~|Rights.statementLocal: Need to obtain permission to publish from original author.
Description.caption: "March 15, 1976Councilman Arthur K. SnyderFourteenth DistrictL.A. City Hall200 North Spring StreetLos Angeles, CA 90012Dear Councilman Snyder:If you are not already aware of the “Snuff” film coming to Los Angeles this week, we wish to bring this to your attention. It will be opening in twenty theaters throughout Los Angeles this Wednesday, March 17, unless people in the community take action to prevent that from happening.This film capitalizes on the murder and dismemberment of a woman. We deplore the violence and utter disrespect for human life epitomized in “Snuff”. Studies have shown that movies like this encourage and foster similar behavior and acts of atrocities in reality.The fact that a movie of the rank caliber of “Snuff” should be shown for popular viewing in our midst is deeply disturbing. We urge you to take every avenue of action open to you to halt the showing of this movie.If your office does not take positive action in this matter, we can only conclude that you condone the showing of this film."

Description.caption: "March 19, 1976Mr. Burt PinesCity AttorneyRoom 1800City Hall EastDear Mr. Pines:I received the attached letter regarding the movie “Snuff.” I was astonished to hear of the violence and utter disrespect for the human life in this movie.I would like you to investigate this matter and reply directly to my office.Thank you for your cooperation.Very sincerely yours,ARTHUR K. SNYDERCouncilman, 14th District"

Project Name: Women Against Violence Against Women (WAVAW) Collection
Name.subject: Women Against Violence Against Women
Title: Campaigns - Other
Description.note: Women Against Violence Against Women Collection: Box 5, 1 Folder; Box 9, 24 Folders.|~|Hillside Strangler memorial demonstration and related correspondence and notes. Correspondence between WAVAW, the Federal Trade Commission (FTC) and U.S. Congressman Edward Roybal re the "Self-Defense" advertising campaign undertaken by Max Factor to promote a new line of cosmetics. Copy of letter sent to Ellen Willis, copy of record reviewer Bruce Dancis' "In These Times" article about WAVAW and copy of response from WAVAW that appeared in March 12, 1979 edition of "In These Times." Press coverage of the Playboy sponsored Hugh M. Hefner First Amendment Awards and press releases and statements for the "WAVAW Hugh Hefner Spirit of Playboy Awards," sponsored by WAVAW, Women Against Violence in Pornography and Media (WAVPM), and Women Against Pornography (WAP). Letters of protest against adult video games such as "Custer's Revenge," "Bachelor Party," and "Beat'em and Eat'em" produced by American Multiple Industries (AMI), response letters from AMI, press releases and publicity articles. Campaigns including: Beulah Land, Dressed to Kill, Bloodline, Windows, Tattoo, Firehouse Rape, Heaven Sent, The Eyes Have It, Killing Us Softly, Seduction, 9 1/2 Weeks, Pieces.
